revision.text:
{{short description|The highly viscous, mechanically weak and ductile region of the Earth's upper mantle}} [[File:subduction-en.svg|thumb|350px|The asthenosphere shown at a [[subduction]] boundary]] The '''asthenosphere''' (from [[Greek language|Greek]] ἀσθενής ''asthenḗs'' 'weak' + "sphere") is the highly viscous, mechanically weak<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Barrel | first1 = J. | year = 1914 | title = The strength of the crust, Part VI. Relations of isostatic movements to a sphere of weakness – the asthenosphere | jstor = 30060774 | journal = The Journal of Geology | volume = 22 | issue = 7 | pages = 655–683 | doi=10.1086/622181 | bibcode=1914JG.....22..655B}}</ref> and [[ductility|ductilely]] deforming region of the upper [[Mantle (geology)|mantle]] of the [[Earth]]. It lies below the [[lithosphere]], at depths between approximately {{convert|80|and|200|km|sigfig=2|abbr=in}} below the surface. The [[Lithosphere-Asthenosphere boundary]] is usually referred to as LAB.<ref>Harsh Gupta (29 June 2011). Encyclopedia of Solid Earth Geophysics. Springer Science & Business Media. pp. 1062–. {{ISBN|978-90-481-8701-0}}.</ref><ref>Lev Eppelbaum; Izzy Kutasov; Arkady Pilchin (29 April 2014). Applied Geothermics.Lev Eppelbaum; Izzy Kutasov; Arkady Pilchin (29 April 2014). Applied Geothermics. Springer Science & Business. pp. 318–. {{ISBN|978-3-642-34023-9}}.Springer Science & Business. pp. 318–. {{ISBN|978-3-642-34023-9}}.</ref> The asthenosphere is almost solid, although some of its regions could be molten (e.g., below [[mid-ocean ridge]]s). The lower boundary of the asthenosphere is not well defined. The thickness of the asthenosphere depends mainly on the temperature. However, the [[rheology]] of the asthenosphere also depends on the rate of deformation,<ref>http://meetingorganizer.copernicus.org/EGU2014/EGU2014-10790.pdf</ref> which suggests that the asthenosphere could be also formed as a result of a high rate of deformation. In some regions the asthenosphere could extend as deep as {{convert|700|km|mi|abbr=on}}. It is considered the source region of mid-ocean ridge [[basalt]] (MORB).<ref> {{cite journal | last1 = Hofmann | first1 = A.W. | year = 1997 | title = Mantle geochemistry: the message from oceanic volcanism | url = https://www.researchgate.net/publication/246759701_Hofmann_A_W_Mantle_geochemistry_The_message_from_oceanic_volcanism_Nature_385_219-229 | journal = Nature | volume = 385 | issue = 6613 | pages = 219–228 | doi=10.1038/385219a0 | bibcode = 1997Natur.385..219H}} </ref>
== Characteristics == The asthenosphere is a part of the upper mantle just below the [[lithosphere]] that is involved in [[Plate tectonics|plate tectonic movement]] and [[Isostasy|isostatic]] adjustments. The lithosphere-asthenosphere boundary is conventionally taken at the 1300&nbsp;°C [[Isotherm (contour line)|isotherm]], above which the mantle behaves in a rigid fashion and below which it behaves in a [[Ductility (Earth science)|ductile]] fashion.<ref name="GeolSoc">{{cite web |url=http://www.geolsoc.org.uk/Education-and-Careers/Resources/Papers-and-Reports/Flood-basalts-mantle-plumes-and-mass-extinctions/The-Crust-and-Lithosphere |title=The Crust and Lithosphere |last1=Self |first1=Steve |last2=Rampino |first2=Mike |publisher=[[Geological Society of London]] |year=2012 |accessdate=27 January 2013}}</ref> [[Seismic wave]]s pass relatively slowly through the asthenosphere<ref>{{cite journal |last=Forsyth |first=Donald W. |title=The early structural evolution and anisotropy of the oceanic upper mantle |url=http://gji.oxfordjournals.org/content/43/1/103 |accessdate=January 24, 2016 |journal=Geophysical Journal International |year=1975 |volume=43 |issue=1 |pages=103–162 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-246X.1975.tb00630.x|bibcode=1975GeoJ...43..103F }}</ref> compared to the overlying lithospheric mantle, thus it has been called the ''[[low-velocity zone]]'' (LVZ), although the two are not exactly the same.<ref>Philip Kearey (17 July 2009). The Encyclopedia of the Solid Earth Sciences. John Wiley & Sons. pp. 36–. {{ISBN|978-1-4443-1388-8}}.</ref><ref>Lev Eppelbaum; Izzy Kutasov; Arkady Pilchin (29 April 2014). Applied Geothermics. Springer Science & Business. pp. 318–. {{ISBN|978-3-642-34023-9}}.</ref> This decreasing in seismic waves velocity from lithosphere to asthenosphere could be caused by the presence of a very small percentage of melt in the asthenosphere. The lower boundary of the LVZ lies at a depth of 180–220&nbsp;km,<ref name="Condie">{{cite book |last=Condie |first=Kent C. |title=Plate tectonics and crustal evolution |publisher=[[Butterworth-Heinemann]] |year=1997 |page=123 |isbn=978-0-7506-3386-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HZrA6OQzsvgC&pg=PA123 |accessdate=21 May 2010}}</ref> whereas the base of the asthenosphere lies at a depth of about 700&nbsp;km.<ref name="Kearey">{{cite book |last1=Kearey |first1=Philip |last2=Vine |first2=Frederick J. |title=Global Tectonics |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=usiqam9p7GAC&pg=RA1-PA41 |accessdate=21 May 2010 |edition=2 |year=1996 |publisher=[[Wiley-Blackwell]] |isbn=978-0-86542-924-6 |pages=41–42}}</ref> This was the observation that originally alerted [[seismology|seismologists]] to its presence and gave some information about its physical properties, as the speed of seismic waves decreases with decreasing [[Stiffness|rigidity]].
In the old [[ocean]]ic [[mantle (geology)|mantle]] the transition from the lithosphere to the asthenosphere, the lithosphere-asthenosphere boundary (LAB) is shallow (about 60&nbsp;km in some regions) with a sharp and large velocity drop (5–10%).<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Rychert |first1=Catherine A. |last2=Shearer |first2=Peter M. |year=2011 |title=Imaging the lithosphere-asthenosphere boundary beneath the Pacific using SS waveform modeling |journal=Journal of Geophysical Research: Solid Earth |volume=116 |issue=B7 |pages= |doi=10.1029/2010JB008070 |url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1029/2010JB008070/full |accessdate=January 24, 2016 |bibcode=2011JGRB..116.7307R}}</ref> At the [[mid-ocean ridge]]s the LAB rises to within a few kilometers of the ocean floor.
The upper part of the asthenosphere is believed to be the zone upon which the great rigid and brittle lithospheric [[tectonic plate|plates of the Earth's crust]] move about. Due to the [[temperature]] and [[pressure]] conditions in the asthenosphere, [[Rock (geology)|rock]] becomes [[ductile]], moving at rates of deformation measured in cm/yr over lineal distances eventually measuring thousands of kilometers. In this way, it flows like a [[convection]] current, radiating heat outward from the Earth's interior. Above the asthenosphere, at the same rate of deformation, rock behaves elastically and, being brittle, can break, causing [[Fault (geology)|faults]]. The rigid lithosphere is thought to "float" or move about on the slowly flowing asthenosphere, creating the movement of [[tectonic plates]].<ref>Mark Hendrix; Graham R. Thompson (24 January 2014). EARTH2. Cengage Learning. pp. 493–. {{ISBN|978-1-305-43687-9}}.</ref><ref>Tom S. Garrison; Robert Ellis (5 December 2016). Essentials of Oceanography. Cengage Learning. pp. 19–. {{ISBN|978-1-337-51538-2}}.</ref>
== Historical == Although its presence was suspected as early as 1926, the worldwide occurrence of the asthenosphere was confirmed by analyses of seismic waves from the 9.5 [[Moment magnitude scale|M<sub>w</sub>]] [[Great Chilean earthquake]] of May 22, 1960.
